<li id="cite_note-54"><b><a href="#cite_ref-54" title="">^</a></b> Oddly listed in the closing credits as <i>spoke</i> Zarathustra but on the official soundtrack albums as <i>spake</i> Zarathustra. The book by Nietzsche has been translated both ways and the title of Strauss's music is usually rendered in the original German whenever not discussed in the context of <i>2001</i>. Although Britannica Online's entry lists the piece as <i>spoke</i> Zarathustra, music encyclopedias usually go with 'spake'. Overall, 'spake' is more common mentioning the Strauss music and 'spoke' more common mentioning the book by Nietzsche.</li>
<li id="cite_note-55"><b><a href="#cite_ref-55" title="">^</a></b> It is possible that the music from "Also Sprach Zarathustra" indirectly inspired some of the crucial scenes, as discussed <a href="http://rambambashi.wordpress.com/2008/09/06/2001-a-space-odyssey-and-zoroastrianism/" class="external text" title="http://rambambashi.wordpress.com/2008/09/06/2001-a-space-odyssey-and-zoroastrianism/" rel="nofollow">here</a>.</li>
